<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-759-020  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 759 020.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  Sept 28 1989 v15 n20 p33(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Firms urged to jump on OSI, MAP and TOP bandwagons. (Open SystemsInterconnection, Manufacturing Automated Protocol and Technicaland Office Protocols)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Barker, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Gary Bray, Senior VP of Marketing for Telecom Canada, tellsdelegates attending a MAP/TOP Users' Group in Toronto thatCanadian companies should support Open Systems Interconnectionstandards as developed by the International Organization forStandardization (ISO).andP;  OSI is an open architecture employingstandard protocols to provide computer-to-computer communication.andO;The goal of these standards, Bray said, is the provision ofenabling technologies that will bring efficient global datacommunications closer to reality.andP;  The Manufacturing AutomatedProtocol and the Technical and Office Protocols provide likeconnectivity for the factory and the office environment based onOSI standards.andP;  The company that wishes to compete successfully inthe future must act now to put information-transferinfrastructures in place.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     StandardsManufacturing Automation Protocol (Computer Network Protocol)Technical and Office Protocol (Computer Network Protocol)OSI StandardConnectivityInternational Trade.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>